<BaseLayout pageTitle={pageTitle}>
  <img
    class="filler"
    src="https://blob.gifcities.org/gifcities/6CR6N74IW2ZRZNDBYCIYUPLJ4K5LG3KN.gif"
  />

  <textarea>
    [This is a fictional story.] There is no definitive answer that explains
    what makes one "one". Many philosophers, scientists, and ordinary people
    have been searching for an answer to explain where we come from and what we
    are. Thanks to all the work that our prior generations have done, we now
    know where we come from; but we have yet to find the reason why, and many,
    if not most or all, struggle with the purpose that their lives ultimately
    serve. I do not remember when I first started to ponder these subjects, but
    I spent many years in my 20s struggling with finding myself. I still do not
    know who I am, and I don't know if I will ever find the answer in my
    lifetime. But after years of struggling, seeking resources, contemplating,
    and getting help from professionals, I can proudly say that I now accept
    myself for who I am, at least for now. Growing up, I loved putting labels on
    myself. I loved calling myself this and that, and I loved taking personality
    tests and some obscure online quizzes to find more labels that suited me. I
    found those so interesting since they could help you define who you are as a
    person, and I could tell people these labels were who I was. I was trying to
    find myself, and I was okay being who I was. But the fun didn't last
    forever; it ended after I was suddenly expected to work as a functional
    member of society, and all of sudden there were labels everywhere coming
    after me. Back in school, I could be myself without any consequences.
    However, that was no longer the case, and now I was expected to perform in a
    certain way, and display certain behaviours that neither my body nor brain
    couldn't agree with. It was then when I first started to wonder, hey, what
    if I'm not normal? Then my whole world shifted and I felt like my whole life
    was denied. I couldn't take that I wasn't who I thought I was, and it made
    me stop being kind to myself. I couldn't accept myself for who I was. Shame,
    pride, difference, weird, useful, useless. I started to blame myself for
    being weak. I desperately wanted proof that I am indeed just like everyone
    else. I've always had a high expectation of myself. I wanted to achieve xyz
    goals by xyz age. I had to be a good kid, and I couldn't turn out like the
    other non-good kids, but it wasn't those expectations from outside that made
    me have so many goals. I had lots of interests in many different things, and
    wanted to be good at all of them. Why? Because being good at something is
    cool, and I was fueled by perks of being young -- not knowing fear and
    having more physical resources. But these goals or dreams I had all came
    back to me to haunt me down when I had grown older and had no achievements
    to show. Show whom? Perhaps the main goal I was going after was to impress
    people with my skills, rather than out of a pure desire to be better at
    something. When I was seeing an occupational therapist earlier this year, I
    mentioned to her how I am disappointed in myself for the lack of interest in
    the things I used to enjoy before. I wasn't playing any musical instruments
    as much, and I couldn't understand why, because I've experimented and played
    with so many different musical instruments. I wasn't creative anymore, when
    I used to draw, paint, or do so much with different mediums and tools. I
    even struggled with finishing video games that I thought I enjoyed. I was
    ashamed of myself and felt like a disgrace. My therapist then asked me "why
    do you have to play piano?" and "why do you have to finish a video game"?,
    and I couldn't really answer those questions. These simple questions that
    she asked were challenging my whole mental system. Was it okay to not play
    piano, or complete books, video games, or art projects? I said to her that I
    feel guilty for not playing piano when it's in my sight. I see my piano, and
    it reminds me how many months or years I've neglected it, and it makes me
    feel bad. She told me to put it away then. Has the answer always been this
    simple? But how about for not completing xyz? "Just have fun", she said
    something like that. It didn't come to my head that what I've doing was
    okay. Had I forgotten how to have fun, and what hobbies are for? Thanks to
    the evolution of technologies and the development of World Wide Web, We live
    in a world where information is easily accessible. But this also acts as a
    double-edged sword; we live in a world with too much information. We are now
    exposed to too many things that we didn't need, which work as additional
    stressors in our lives. Years ago, the ultimate goal for humans as animals
    was to survive. However, this goal has now transformed into being good, or
    the best. The traits that would've been characteristics of someone can now
    be viewed as flaws. An average person, who is a single entity, can now
    interact with an unimaginable number of people, and unfortunately this means
    we are more prone to be exposed to negativity. Also this massive web of data
    has contributed to creating fake community bubbles or echo chambers. We as
    social animals tend to socialize with those who are similar to us. But these
    echo chambers, when used by individuals not knowing these are echo chambers,
    are causing many people to have skewed views on their beliefs or biases,
    creating extreme divisions between people. Unfortunately the platform that
    had made it easier for people to communicate is making it harder for people
    to communicate. There is too much information versus time and intelligence
    we have to absorb or fact-check. Companies are constantly spending billions
    of dollars on finding ways to monetize and increase their profits. With the
    increase of bot activities and the rise of LLMs, there is more generated
    content than ever. Of course, I could be biased. We all want to be perfect,
    though we struggle to be normal. Perfect: rich, fit, physically attractive,
    smart, any other traits that are looked upon. We all want to be normal,
    though our bar for normal is way above average. Normal: healthy physically
    and mentally, financially stable, able to support and raise family. The
    complex human brain tends to forget that we are simply biological organisms
    with finite resources and a finite lifespan. Even machines degrade and
    malfunction. Their functionalities are tied to their hardware. But we often
    are tricked into thinking that the reason we cannot achieve what others do
    is entirely our own fault. I like the metaphor of comparing humans to
    machines, or computers specifically. We can only store so much information,
    process so much, and this all depends on individual's capabilities. What is
    normal for one does not mean it's normal for others. The illusion of being
    healthy is impossible to achieve, when we are not machines with replaceable
    parts, but living beings stuck in lifecycles. As a living organism ages, its
    functions start to degrade -- at least I haven't heard of a single human who
    is immortal as of now. Also what defines healthy? Not having diseases and
    disorders? What are diseases and disorders? Words are abstract made up
    concepts that are used to describe phenomena or traits, which can be
    interpreted differently by each individual. I'll probably update this part
    after finishing the book I'm reading, the Myth of Normal. It was only
    recently that I've truly accepted that I do not fit in with the typical
    people. I'd been suspecting it for years, talked to multiple friends and
    sought help from professionals. Unfortunately it is hard to diagnose and
    accept a non-visible condition. I've received misdiagnosis, due to many
    reasons with the lack of my awareness being one of them. Only last year,
    when I found my old report cards with written records of my childhood
    behaviours, was I able to accept that I have always been different from what
    is perceived as normal. It also came with lots of regrets and what-ifs. What
    if I had known this earlier? What if I had continued my treatment? What
    if... It also came with lots of look backs. I realized that things I thought
    everyone was going through were not what everyone was going through.
    Different individuals have different experiences, which is quite obvious
    since we are all born with different sets of genes and are raised in
    different environments, experiencing different things. There was a lot of
    negativity in me that I did not understand myself. I was conflicted. I was
    unhappy with myself. I blamed myself for being someone I didn't wish to be.
    I just wanted to be normal. I did not eat or move. I spent days and months
    in bed, just sleeping, hoping that in another world that I could be free
    from this meat prison that is my body. I hated myself for being lazy. People
    have told me that I am hard on myself. I was kind to other people. Yet I
    wasn't kind to myself. I let myself go, stopped taking care of myself, and
    just let myself be. And yet, I thought I was acting like a snowflake, and
    questioned my own not-well-being. I couldn't afford to be this way because I
    had too many responsibilities and too much to take care of. I couldn't let
    my family down. I had to be respected. I had to be successful. I had to be
    useful. I had to be perfect. I had to be normal. Other people have problems
    too. Other people suffer. You are such a snowflake. Shut the fuck up.
    Thankfully, I was able to receive help from multiple professionals. Not
    because I was actively seeking it, but because my health insurance company
    made me. I started to receive therapies which I had been avoiding, because I
    thought I had no problems to talk about. I was supposely doing well, and was
    supposed to have no problems, because others are suffering more. Funnily, I
    had recommended therapies to other people, and was impressed by people who
    would openly tell me that they are seeing therapists. But it was never an
    option for me. Also I started my medical treatment again. I started to read
    about people who share the same hardship, and read books written by medical
    doctors known in the field. I had to confront my past experiences that made
    me who I am now. I had to accept that I am only a human, and that I am not
    perfect. But I also couldn't be fixed, because I'm not a machine, but a
    human. I learned that some of my past experiences were indeed traumas.
    Having traumas and medical conditions were all taboos for me, things I
    wasn't allowed to have or show signs of. But they were me after all these
    times. I still struggled to accept who I am. I was especially harsh on my
    inner child. I had an image of a functional adult that I had to fit in, and
    it took me a very long time to finally let go of it. I had been denying my
    inner child, but have finally embraced it as part of me. I am allowed to
    have some fun or show signs of weaknesses, and that does not necessarily
    mean I'm incompetent or a failure. I worked towards success, but it was only
    after facing my scars and impurities, I was able to let it go. It's not
    success that I am after, but happiness. My current goal is to be content
    with what I have. All will be gone after my body perishes anyway; I will
    join the world as just a group of atoms which will eventually scatter away.
    I will join the stars and the universe. I am finite. I have limited
    resources. I am not all. But at least I can be myself, and live my life.
  </textarea>
